Juveniles from Belize and Costa Rica are more distinctly banded or ocellated than adults and lack the strongly contrasting red head and tail characteristic of adults (
Fig. 17
;
Stafford & Meyer 2000
: pl. 112 ;
Savage 2002
: pl. 414 ;
Solórzano 2004
: fig. 56 ). The photographs of juveniles show reddish brown to orangish brown tones on the top of the head (especially anterior to the eyes) but the tail appears brown to dark brown with only hints of red, and only slightly paler than the rest of the dorsum. The dorsum is brown anteriorly to blackish posteriorly with a series of pale grayish to yellowish ocelli the length of the body and pale flecking on the vertebral row.
